 -- Jason Gerard DeRose <jason@system76.com>  Thu, 14 Jul 2016 14:09:13 -0600

system76-driver (16.04.6) xenial; urgency=low

  * Revert changes from unpublished 16.04.5
  * Add `system76-fix-ecryptfs-swap` script to work-around ecryptfs-setup-swap
    failing to mark GPT swap partitions as non-auto-mounting on NVMe drives
    (see https://bugs.launchpad.net/ecryptfs/+bug/1597154)
  * debian/system76-driver.postinst: on configure, automatically call
    system76-fix-ecryptfs-swap; this is a quick work-around to prevent users
    with NVME + nvidia-367 + encrypted home directory from being left with an
    un-bootable system after upgrading to nvidia-367

 -- Jason Gerard DeRose <jason@system76.com>  Wed, 29 Jun 2016 16:42:45 -0600

system76-driver (16.04.5) xenial; urgency=low

  * To temporarily work-around the consequences of lp:1597154, re-enable
    GRUB_GFXPAYLOAD_LINUX=text line on bonw10, orxp1, serw9
  * Note: 16.04.5 was never published to ppa:system76-dev/stable, was only
    published to ppa:system76-dev/pre-stable

 -- David Jordan <david2@system76.com>  Wed, 29 Jun 2016 09:09:15 -0600

system76-driver (16.04.4) xenial; urgency=low

  * Add actions.remove_gfxpayload_text to remove GRUB_GFXPAYLOAD_LINUX=text line
  * On bonw10, orxp1, serw9, replace gfxpayload_text action with
    remove_gfxpayload_text
  * Add /lib/systemd/system-sleep/system76-nm-restart script to restart
    network-manager 1 second after resuming from suspend; this works around WiFi
    reliability problems when resuming from suspend with Intel 7260 WiFi cards
    on Xenial
  * debian/control: system76-driver-nvidia now depends on nvidia-367 (in prep
    for GTX 1080, GTX 1070)
  * system76-nvidia-quirks: update Handler to "nvidia-367|nvidia-340"

